#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:1
msgid "`impl Trait` for returning complex types with ease"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.26](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.26-brightgreen.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:5
msgid ""
"`impl Trait` is the new way to specify unnamed but concrete types that "
"implement a specific trait. There are two places you can put it: argument "
"position, and return position."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:11
msgid "// argument position\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:15
msgid "// return position\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:21
msgid "Argument Position"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:23
msgid ""
"In argument position, this feature is quite simple. These two forms are "
"almost the same:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:36
msgid ""
"That is, it's a slightly shorter syntax for a generic type parameter. It "
"means, \"`arg` is an argument that takes any type that implements the "
"`Trait` trait.\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:40
msgid ""
"However, there's also an important technical difference between `T: Trait` "
"and `impl Trait` here. When you write the former, you can specify the type "
"of `T` at the call site with turbo-fish syntax as with `foo::<usize>(1)`. In "
"the case of `impl Trait`, if it is used anywhere in the function definition, "
"then you can't use turbo-fish at all. Therefore, you should be mindful that "
"changing both from and to `impl Trait` can constitute a breaking change for "
"the users of your code."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:48
msgid "Return Position"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:50
msgid ""
"In return position, this feature is more interesting. It means \"I am "
"returning some type that implements the `Trait` trait, but I'm not going to "
"tell you exactly what the type is.\" Before `impl Trait`, you could do this "
"with trait objects:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:65
msgid ""
"However, this has some overhead: the `Box<T>` means that there's a heap "
"allocation here, and this will use dynamic dispatch. See the `dyn Trait` "
"section for an explanation of this syntax. But we only ever return one "
"possible thing here, the `Box<i32>`. This means that we're paying for "
"dynamic dispatch, even though we don't use it!"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:71
msgid "With `impl Trait`, the code above could be written like this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:83
msgid ""
"Here, we have no `Box<T>`, no trait object, and no dynamic dispatch. But we "
"still can obscure the `i32` return type."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:86
msgid ""
"With `i32`, this isn't super useful. But there's one major place in Rust "
"where this is much more useful: closures."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:89
msgid "`impl Trait` and closures"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:91
msgid ""
"If you need to catch up on closures, check out [their chapter in the book]"
"(https://doc.rust-lang.org/book/second-edition/ch13-01-closures.html)."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:94
msgid ""
"In Rust, closures have a unique, un-writable type. They do implement the "
"`Fn` family of traits, however. This means that previously, the only way to "
"return a closure from a function was to use a trait object:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:104
msgid ""
"You couldn't write the type of the closure, only use the `Fn` trait. That "
"means that the trait object is necessary. However, with `impl Trait`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:113
msgid "We can now return closures by value, just like any other type!"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:115
msgid "More details"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:117
msgid ""
"The above is all you need to know to get going with `impl Trait`, but for "
"some more nitty-gritty details: type parameters and `impl Trait` work "
"slightly differently when they're in argument position versus return "
"position. Consider this function:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:126
msgid ""
"When you call it, you set the type, `T`. \"you\" being the caller here. This "
"signature says \"I accept any type that implements Trait.\" (\"any type\" == "
"universal in the jargon)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:130
msgid "This version:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:136
msgid ""
"is similar, but also different. You, the caller, provide the type you want, "
"`T`, and then the function returns it. You can see this in Rust today with "
"things like parse or collect:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:141
#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:142
msgid "\"5\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:145
msgid "Here, `.parse` has this signature:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:152
msgid ""
"Same general idea, though with a result type and `FromStr` has an associated "
"type... anyway, you can see how `F` is in the return position here. So you "
"have the ability to choose."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:156
msgid ""
"With `impl Trait`, you're saying \"hey, some type exists that implements "
"this trait, but I'm not gonna tell you what it is.\". So now, the caller "
"can't choose, and the function itself gets to choose. If we tried to define "
"parse with `Result<impl F,...` as the return type, it wouldn't work."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:161
msgid "Using `impl Trait` in more places"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/trait-system/impl-trait-for-returning-complex-types-with-ease.md:163
msgid ""
"As previously mentioned, as a start, you will only be able to use `impl "
"Trait` as the argument or return type of a free or inherent function. "
"However, `impl Trait` can't be used inside implementations of traits, nor "
"can it be used as the type of a let binding or inside a type alias. Some of "
"these restrictions will eventually be lifted. For more information, see the "
"[tracking issue on `impl Trait`](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/"
"issues/34511)."
msgstr ""
